SQL OR Operator

The SQL OR operator is used in the WHERE clause to filter records based on more than one condition.
A record is returned when any one of the conditions joined by OR evaluates to TRUE.

OR Syntax:
SELECT column1, column2, ...
FROM table_name
WHERE condition1 OR condition2 OR condition3 ...;

Example 1: Simple OR Condition
Select all customers where Country is Germany or Spain:
SELECT *
FROM Customers
WHERE Country = 'Germany' OR Country = 'Spain';

What this does:
This query returns rows where Country is either Germany or Spain.
When to use it:
Use this when any one of several options should be accepted.

Example 2: OR with multiple values
Select customers from Germany, Spain, or Mexico:
SELECT CustomerID, CustomerName, Country
FROM Customers
WHERE Country = 'Germany' OR Country = 'Spain' OR Country = 'Mexico';

What this does:
This query returns rows matching any of the listed countries.
When to use it:
Use this for a set of possible values without using IN.

Example 3: OR with text pattern matching
Select customers in Berlin or whose name starts with G:
SELECT CustomerID, CustomerName, City, Country
FROM Customers
WHERE City = 'Berlin' OR CustomerName LIKE 'G%';

What this does:
This query returns customers who are either in Berlin or have names beginning with G.
When to use it:
Use this when you want either of two different filter types.

Example 4: OR with a non-existent value
Select customers in London or Norway:
SELECT CustomerID, CustomerName, City, Country
FROM Customers
WHERE City = 'London' OR Country = 'Norway';

What this does:
This query returns customers in London or any customers from Norway if they exist.
When to use it:
Use this when one of the conditions may not match any rows.

Example 5: OR with numeric and text conditions
Select customers with CustomerID 1 or city Mexico City:
SELECT CustomerID, CustomerName, City, Country
FROM Customers
WHERE CustomerID = 1 OR City = 'Mexico City';

What this does:
This query returns the row with ID 1 or any customer located in Mexico City.
When to use it:
Use this to combine a specific row choice with a location filter.

Example 6: OR with IN as an alternative
The IN operator is often easier to read than multiple OR conditions:
SELECT CustomerID, CustomerName, Country
FROM Customers
WHERE Country IN ('Germany', 'Spain', 'Mexico');

What this does:
This query returns rows where Country matches any listed value.
When to use it:
Use this when you want a cleaner alternative to many OR clauses.

Example 7: OR with ORDER BY
Select customers from Germany or Sweden and sort by CustomerName:
SELECT CustomerID, CustomerName, Country
FROM Customers
WHERE Country = 'Germany' OR Country = 'Sweden'
ORDER BY CustomerName;

What this does:
This query returns German and Swedish customers sorted by name.
When to use it:
Use this when you want ordered results from an OR filter.

Example 8: OR with LIMIT
Select the first 3 German or Spanish customers:
SELECT CustomerID, CustomerName, Country
FROM Customers
WHERE Country = 'Germany' OR Country = 'Spain'
LIMIT 3;

What this does:
This query returns only the first three matching rows.
When to use it:
Use this when you want a limited sample of OR-filtered results.

AND vs OR
----------
- AND requires all conditions to be TRUE.
- OR requires only one of the conditions to be TRUE.

Example 9: OR only
SELECT CustomerID, CustomerName, Country
FROM Customers
WHERE Country = 'Spain' OR Country = 'Mexico';

What this does:
This query returns rows from either Spain or Mexico.
When to use it:
Use this when either condition is acceptable.

Example 10: AND only
SELECT CustomerID, CustomerName, Country
FROM Customers
WHERE Country = 'Spain' AND City = 'Madrid';

What this does:
This query returns rows where both conditions hold.
When to use it:
Use this when every condition must be true.

Combining AND and OR
--------------------
When you combine AND and OR, use parentheses to make sure SQL evaluates the conditions correctly.

Example 11: OR inside AND
Select Spanish customers that start with G or R:
SELECT *
FROM Customers
WHERE Country = 'Spain' AND (CustomerName LIKE 'G%' OR CustomerName LIKE 'R%');

What this does:
This query returns Spanish customers whose names begin with G or R.
When to use it:
Use this when one strict condition and one flexible condition are required.

Example 12: No parentheses changes meaning
Without parentheses, the query returns all Spanish customers whose name starts with G,
plus all customers whose name starts with R regardless of country:
SELECT *
FROM Customers
WHERE Country = 'Spain' AND CustomerName LIKE 'G%' OR CustomerName LIKE 'R%';

What this does:
This query applies AND before OR and changes the result set.
When to use it:
Be careful: use parentheses when intent depends on condition grouping.

Example 13: OR with AND groups
Select customers from Mexico or the UK whose name starts with A:
SELECT CustomerID, CustomerName, Country
FROM Customers
WHERE (Country = 'Mexico' OR Country = 'UK')
  AND CustomerName LIKE 'A%';

What this does:
This query returns A-name customers in either Mexico or the UK.
When to use it:
Use this to mix grouped OR conditions with an AND filter.

Example 14: OR with NOT
Select customers not from Germany or Mexico:
SELECT CustomerID, CustomerName, Country
FROM Customers
WHERE Country <> 'Germany' OR Country <> 'Mexico';

What this does:
This query returns all rows because one of the OR conditions is always true.
When to use it:
Use this as a cautionary example: prefer AND for excluding multiple values.

Example 15: OR with BETWEEN
Select customers in Germany or with CustomerID between 1 and 5:
SELECT CustomerID, CustomerName, Country
FROM Customers
WHERE Country = 'Germany' OR CustomerID BETWEEN 1 AND 5;

What this does:
This query returns German customers and any customers with ID 1-5.
When to use it:
Use this when you need either a categorical value or a numeric range.

Example 16: OR with LIKE and multiple patterns
Select customers whose name starts with A or B:
SELECT CustomerID, CustomerName
FROM Customers
WHERE CustomerName LIKE 'A%' OR CustomerName LIKE 'B%';

What this does:
This query returns customers with names beginning with A or B.
When to use it:
Use this to match multiple text patterns.

